            // C takes 6/2=3 (N=3). O takes 1 (N=2). C takes 1 (N=1). O takes 1 (N=0). C: 3+1=4, O: 1+1=2.
            // Both give 4. The example says C takes 3. So C takes N/2.
            // Consider N = 8.
            // C takes 1 (N=7). O takes 1 (N=6). C takes 3 (N=3). O takes 1 (N=2). C takes 1 (N=1). O takes 1 (N=0). C: 1+3+1=5, O: 1+1+1=3.
            // C takes 8/2=4 (N=4). O takes 2 (N=2). C takes 1 (N=1). O takes 1 (N=0). C: 4+1=5, O: 2+1=3.
            // Both give 5.
            // It seems taking N/2 is always optimal for Chanek if N is even, unless N/2 is 1 (i.e., N=2).
            // The only exception is when N is a power of 2, and N/2 is also a power of 2, and so on, until N becomes 2.
