    // If P1 is a palindrome, and s is a palindrome, and not all chars are same,
    // then we can always find a cut.
    // Example: "abacaba"
    // P1 = "aba", P2 = "c", P3 = "aba"
    // P1 is a palindrome.
    // P1 + P2 + P3 = "abacaba"
    // P3 + P2 + P1 = "abacaba"
    // This specific cut doesn't work if P1 is a palindrome.
    //
    // However, the problem statement guarantees that if not all characters are the same,
    // k=2 is always possible.
    // The example "nolon" -> "onlno" uses cuts "no|l|on" and reorders to "on|l|no".
    // This is P1 = "no", P2 = "l", P3 = "on".
    // P3 is reverse(P1).
    // The new string is P3 + P2 + P1.
    // This is a palindrome.
    // Is P3 + P2 + P1 == P1 + P2 + P3?
    // This implies P3 == P1.
    // Which means reverse(P1) == P1.
    // So, if P1 is NOT a palindrome, then P3 + P2 + P1 is different from P1 + P2 + P3.
    // If P1 is NOT a palindrome, then k=2 works.
