        //     We must use a head `h[h_idx]` such that `h[h_idx] - T <= p[p_idx]`.
        //     We want to pick the head that covers `p[p_idx]` and extends furthest to the right.
        //     Iterate `h_idx` forward:
        //       Find the first `h[h_idx]` such that `h[h_idx] - T <= p[p_idx]`.
        //       If no such `h[h_idx]` exists (i.e., `h_idx == n` or `h[h_idx] - T > p[p_idx]` for all remaining heads):
        //         Then `p[p_idx]` cannot be covered. Return `false`.
        //       Among all such `h[h_idx]` that satisfy `h[h_idx] - T <= p[p_idx]`,
        //       we need to pick one that maximizes `h[h_idx] + T`.
        //       This is equivalent to picking the `h[h_idx]` that is furthest to the right,
        //       while still being able to cover `p[p_idx]`.
        //       So, we should pick the largest `h[h_idx]` such that `h[h_idx] - T <= p[p_idx]`.
        //       Let this be `h_best`.
