                      // If l is odd and r is odd, and r > l, then r must be at least l+2.
                      // E.g., l=3, r=5. Range [3,4,5]. 4 is even. So 2 is a divisor.
                      // So, if l is odd and r is odd, the only way for no even numbers to be in the range is if r=l.
                      // In this specific case (l=r and l is odd), 2 cannot be the answer.
                      // Any divisor of l is equally frequent (once). So l is a valid answer.
                      // In all other cases, there is at least one even number in the range [l, r].
                      // So 2 is a divisor of at least one number. Its count is at least 1.
                      // Since 2 is the smallest prime, it will generally have the highest count.
                      // If there's a tie (like 3 6, where count(2)=2, count(3)=2), 2 is a valid answer.
                      // So, the logic is:
                      // If l == r and l % 2 == 1: print l
                      // Else: print 2

    if (l == r && l % 2 == 1) {
        std::cout << l << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << 2 << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

